Alright—here’s a **clean, step-by-step CLI guide** to create an **Amazon EKS** cluster from your EC2 Ubuntu machine.

I’ll use the simplest and most reliable tool: **eksctl** (this avoids a lot of manual pain).

---

# 🧭 Step-by-step: Create EKS cluster from CLI

## ✅ Step 1: Install AWS CLI

```bash
curl "https://awscli.amazonaws.com/awscli-exe-linux-x86_64.zip" -o "awscliv2.zip"
unzip awscliv2.zip
sudo ./aws/install
```

Verify:

```bash
aws --version
```

---

## ✅ Step 2: Configure AWS credentials

```bash
aws configure
```

Enter:

* Access Key
* Secret Key
* Region (e.g. `ap-south-1`)
* Output format: `json`

---

## ✅ Step 3: Install eksctl

```bash
curl --silent --location "https://github.com/weaveworks/eksctl/releases/latest/download/eksctl_$(uname -s)_amd64.tar.gz" | tar xz -C /tmp

sudo mv /tmp/eksctl /usr/local/bin
```

Verify:

```bash
eksctl version
```

---

## ✅ Step 4: Install kubectl

```bash
curl -LO "https://dl.k8s.io/release/$(curl -L -s https://dl.k8s.io/release/stable.txt)/bin/linux/amd64/kubectl"

chmod +x kubectl
sudo mv kubectl /usr/local/bin/
```

Verify:

```bash
kubectl version --client
```

---

## 🚀 Step 5: Create EKS cluster

### Basic command:

```bash
eksctl create cluster \
  --name my-cluster \
  --region ap-south-1 \
  --nodegroup-name my-nodes \
  --node-type t3.medium \
  --nodes 2
```

---

### ⏳ What happens now

This will automatically:

* Create VPC
* Create EKS control plane
* Launch EC2 worker nodes
* Configure networking

⏱ Takes ~10–20 minutes

---

## ✅ Step 6: Verify cluster

```bash
kubectl get nodes
```

You should see:

```id="sample"
NAME           STATUS   ROLES    AGE   VERSION
ip-...         Ready    <none>   ...   ...
```

---

## ✅ Step 7: Test deployment

```bash
kubectl create deployment nginx --image=nginx
kubectl expose deployment nginx --type=LoadBalancer --port=80
```

Then:

```bash
kubectl get svc
```

👉 This time, **EXTERNAL-IP will work** because EKS integrates with AWS 🎯

---

# ⚠️ Important tips

### 💸 Cost warning

EKS is **not free**:

* Control plane ≈ $0.10/hour
* EC2 nodes cost extra

---

### 🔐 IAM permissions needed

Your AWS user/role must allow:

* EKS
* EC2
* CloudFormation
* IAM

---

### 🧹 Delete cluster (VERY IMPORTANT)

When done:

```bash
eksctl delete cluster --name my-cluster --region ap-south-1
```

---

# 🧠 Why this works (vs your current setup)

* Kind / kubeadm → no AWS integration ❌
* EKS → fully integrated → LoadBalancer works ✅

